In Java, **instance variables** (also known as **fields**) are variables that are declared inside a class but outside any methods, constructors, or blocks. These variables represent the **attributes** or **state** of an object. Each object created from the class has its own copy of these instance variables.

**Syntax:**

```java
class Seedit {
    // Instance variables (fields)
    String studentName;  // Name of the student
    int studentScore;    // Score of the student

    // Method to display student information
    public void displayInfo() {
        // Accessing instance variables directly
        System.out.println("Student Name: " + studentName);
        System.out.println("Student Score: " + studentScore);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Create an object of the SEED-IT class
        SEED-IT student = new SEED-IT();  // Object creation using the class constructor

        // Set values to the instance variables using dot notation
        student.studentName = "John";  // Dot notation used to assign value to studentName
        student.studentScore = 85;  // Dot notation used to assign value to studentScore

        // Call method to display student information using dot notation
        student.displayInfo();  // Dot notation used to call the displayInfo method
    }
}


```


**Expected Output:**

```default
Student Name: John
Student Score: 85
```

